data.content:
This code **does not use `Thread.Abort`** — so there's no `Thread.Abort` migration issue here. It will compile and run on .NET 8 as-is.

That said, two things worth noting for this migration:

**1. Closure bug (pre-C# 5):** If targeting older C# versions, `item` in the lambda captures the loop variable. Modern C# (5+) scopes `foreach` variables per iteration, so this is fine on .NET 8.

**2. Modernization opportunity:** Manual `Thread` management is outdated. The idiomatic .NET 8 equivalent:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
        {
            await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);
        });
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**General `Thread.Abort` migration guidance** (for when you do encounter it elsewhere):

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Use `CancellationToken` — throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8 |
| `Thread.Abort()` + catch `ThreadAbortException` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` or call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` |
| Timeout-based abort | Use `CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan)` |

The core pattern:

```csharp
// Instead of: thread.Abort()
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
var task = Task.Run(() => DoWork(cts.Token), cts.Token);
cts.Cancel();  // cooperative cancellation
```

Your code is already safe — just a good candidate for modernization with `Task`/`Parallel`.
